   =20
      Insider trading (1)
   =20
 =20
I assume that most people who work in compliance at big investment banks ar=
e good, upstanding, compliant people, but I also get the impression that th=
ere is a small but important minority who got into the compliance group bec=
ause they thought it would be a good place to commit crimes?  Oops:A former=
 Goldman Sachs Group Inc. compliance analyst whose job was to help the bank=
 prevent insider trading was himself charged with insider trading by the Se=
curities and Exchange Commission.The SEC sued Jose Luis Casero Sanchez on W=
ednesday, claiming he used his position in the bank=E2=80=99s Warsaw office=
 to access a control room which stored confidential information on =E2=80=
=9Call pending and potential transactions in which the investment bank was =
involved and advising clients.=E2=80=9D He made at least $471,700 in illega=
l trading profits, the regulator said.Look, it is=C2=A0a good place to comm=
it crimes! =E2=80=9CNobody suspects the compliance analyst=E2=80=9D would b=
e a funny thing to say but isn=E2=80=99t particularly true; I bet everyone =
suspects the compliance analyst. The real advantage is access to informatio=
n.=C2=A0If you go to Goldman and work as an investment banking analyst, you=
 will know about the handful of mergers that you are working on, and you wi=
ll certainly hear about=C2=A0some other mergers that your friends are worki=
ng on, but there are at least vague gestures in the direction of compartmen=
talization and confidentiality even within the firm, and anyway you=C2=A0ar=
e mostly busy on your own deals, not gossiping about everyone else=E2=80=99=
s.=C2=A0Nobody is going to hand you a list of =E2=80=9Chere is every merger=
 we are working on.=E2=80=9DWhereas they did hand Casero Sanchez that list.=
 From the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint:One of Sanchez=E2=80=99s duties was to up=
date the firm=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CGrey List,=E2=80=9D which is a confidentia=
l list of public and private entities for which the firm=E2=80=99s private-=
side personnel possess material, nonpublic information.Typically, Grey List=
 entities are involved in merger and acquisition activity and financings su=
ch as public and private securities offerings, among other things. If an en=
tity is on the Grey List, certain controls at the Investment Bank may be im=
plicated, including but not limited to, surveillance of firm and client tra=
ding activities in the securities of the company on the list, and the denia=
l of certain employees=E2=80=99 personal trade requests in the securities o=
f the company on the list.=C2=A0The Grey List is maintained on an internal =
database at the Investment Bank (the =E2=80=9CConfidential Database=E2=80=
=9D). The Confidential Database is the depository where material,=C2=A0nonp=
ublic information about potential transactions involving the Investment Ban=
k is stored. For each transaction, the Confidential Database may include, b=
ut is not limited to: the names of the public and private entities involved=
 in the potential or pending transaction; the firm=E2=80=99s role in the tr=
ansaction; the nature of the transaction; the securities involved; the type=
 of financing involved; the size of the transaction; pricing information; t=
he projected announcement date; and other material, nonpublic details regar=
ding the potential transaction.If someone hands you the passwords to a data=
base and is like =E2=80=9Chere is a comprehensive list of all the stocks th=
at we wouldn=E2=80=99t want anyone to insider trade on=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0you can see the temptation right?Anyway if you=E2=80=99re an inves=
tment banking analyst and you work on like four deals and insider trade on =
all of them, there are some problems; you only have a few shots to make mon=
ey and you might find yourself reaching for profits by buying short-dated o=
ut-of-the-money call options on merger targets, a violation of my Second La=
w of Insider Trading. If you=E2=80=99re a compliance analyst with access to=
 the comprehensive database of all deals, you can insider trade at a more l=
eisurely pace. From the SEC=E2=80=99s press release:Between September 2020 =
and May 2021, Sanchez allegedly abused that position of trust by trading on=
 at least 45 events involving the investment bank=E2=80=99s clients based o=
n the investment bank=E2=80=99s material, nonpublic information. To avoid d=
etection, Sanchez allegedly traded in multiple U.S.-based brokerage account=
s held in the name of one of his parents=E2=80=94Jose Luis Casero Abellan a=
nd Maria Isabel Sanchez Gonzalez =E2=80=94and, in most instances, also refr=
ained from placing large trades and made only modest profits. The complaint=
 alleges that Sanchez generated more than $471,000 in ill-gotten gains duri=
ng the course of the scheme.Well, he allegedly violated the Fourth Law of I=
nsider Trading (=E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t do it in your mother=E2=80=99s accou=
nt=E2=80=9D), but all in all it=E2=80=99s a respectable effort. The SEC wen=
t out of its way to say that he was hard to catch:=E2=80=9CDespite Sanchez=
=E2=80=99s alleged efforts to avoid detection by limiting the size of his t=
rades and using four different accounts to trade under his parents=E2=80=99=
 names, the SEC=E2=80=99s keen analysis stitched together this pattern of s=
uspicious trading and exposed gross violations of duty by a compliance prof=
essional who exploited the sensitive information he was hired to protect.=
=E2=80=9D said Joseph G. Sansone, Chief of the SEC=E2=80=99s Market Abuse U=
nit.How many other compliance analysts out there are just a little bit bett=
er at covering their tracks?
