   =20
      Proxy voting
   =20
 =20
I suppose somewhere out there there are people who are deeply engaged share=
holders of one company. Each year these people get the company=E2=80=99s pr=
oxy statement and read it cover to cover with great interest. Toward the ba=
ck there are some shareholder proposals, in which shareholders get to sugge=
st changes to how the company is run. These proposals typically have an env=
ironmental, social or governance (ESG) flavor: A proposal might be =E2=80=
=9Cthe company should do a report about how climate change will affect its =
operations,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe company should do a report about the d=
iversity of its managerial ranks,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe company should s=
eparate the jobs of chairman of the board and chief executive officer.=E2=
=80=9D These proposals are nonbinding and, under Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission rules, cannot=C2=A0involve =E2=80=9Ca matter relating to the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s ordinary business operations,=E2=80=9D so in practice they oft=
en involve asking for reports rather than, like, =E2=80=9Cresolved, the com=
pany will stop using fossil fuels.=E2=80=9DThe proposal will come with a li=
ttle=C2=A0statement from the proponent, the (usually small, activist) share=
holder who suggested it, and also a little=C2=A0statement from the company=
=E2=80=99s board of directors, almost invariably recommending that sharehol=
ders vote against the proposal. Our deeply engaged single-stock shareholder=
 will read both statements carefully and think about the arguments that the=
 proponent and the board make.=C2=A0She will weigh them in the context of h=
er knowledge of the company. =E2=80=9CHmm,=E2=80=9D she will say, =E2=80=9C=
I see what this person is saying about how separating the chairman and CEO =
roles is best practice, but old Jim has done a great job as CEO and I=E2=80=
=99d hate to risk upsetting him by taking away the chairman job.=E2=80=9D O=
r: =E2=80=9CI would like to know about how climate change will affect the c=
ompany, but I think the board=E2=80=99s track record on that is pretty good=
 so I guess I will defer to them.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6=C2=A0and t=
he board=E2=80=99s track record on that is pretty bad so I=E2=80=99ll vote =
to demand more from them.=E2=80=9D Whatever.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t believe t=
here are too many of these people but they probably exist. More than indivi=
dual investors, some number of active stock-picking money managers probably=
 own a relatively small number of stocks, track them carefully and vote reg=
ularly on their proxy proposals. These money managers=C2=A0probably do not =
read the proxies as closely as our hypothetical engaged retail shareholder =
does. They do this a lot.=C2=A0They have heuristics. Maybe they vote agains=
t most of these proposals, assuming that they=E2=80=99re nonbinding and a w=
aste of time. Maybe their heuristic is =E2=80=9Cwe vote with management in =
the companies that we like, but we vote against management on everything in=
 companies where we dislike the board and are agitating for change.=E2=80=
=9D Maybe they have issue-specific heuristics, =E2=80=9Cwe vote for climate=
-change reports but against diversity reports=E2=80=9D or whatever. Probabl=
y they have some mishmash of all of these heuristics, and vote different wa=
ys for different proposals at different companies, but they don=E2=80=99t s=
pend=C2=A0too=C2=A0much time thinking about it. These are not retail hobbyi=
sts; they have a job to do (buying stocks that go up), and voting on proxy =
proposals is not central to that job.It=E2=80=99s not irrelevant! Pressurin=
g companies to do ESG things can increase their long-term value. A company =
that has a poison pill or a staggered board might be less likely to be acqu=
ired, and depending on your view of whether that would be good or bad for t=
he value of your stock, you might care very much about voting on proposals =
to get rid of a pill or to declassify the board. If you think that climate =
change will be very bad for the company and that the board isn=E2=80=99t pa=
ying attention, you will care a lot about getting the board to pay attentio=
n, and a nonbinding request for a report on climate change is, you know, on=
e more thing you could do to get the board to pay attention I guess. But mo=
stly this stuff is pretty minor. Companies make money based mostly on how t=
hey do their ordinary business, which is specifically off-limits to shareho=
lder proposals. And even on the big-ticket stuff, companies seem to be more=
 responsive to other forms of pressure (quiet nudges from big shareholders,=
 social and customer pressure,  proxy fights) than they are to nonbinding p=
roposals submitted by small shareholders.Then there are professional money =
managers who own hundreds of stocks, perhaps all of the stocks, index funds=
 and =E2=80=9Cquasi-indexers.=E2=80=9D It seems silly for these professiona=
ls to read the proxies at all. (I=E2=80=99m sure they do =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
y have governance and stewardship teams to do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it se=
ems silly.) Certainly if they have to vote on 100 shareholder proposals to =
write climate reports in a proxy season, it would be silly for them to read=
=C2=A0each=C2=A0of the proponents=E2=80=99 arguments and=C2=A0each=C2=A0of =
the companies=E2=80=99 responses. They=E2=80=99ve seen all this before.At t=
his level it is all heuristics. =E2=80=9CVote yes on climate proposals=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cvote with management unless we have a little red frowny =
face next to the company in our huge spreadsheet of investments=E2=80=9D or=
 whatever it is. If you own every company, you can=E2=80=99t have a close p=
ersonal substantive relationship with all of them; you can=E2=80=99t waste =
an hour thinking about whether=C2=A0this=C2=A0particular board of directors=
 should or should not write a report about climate change. You have to have=
 a general sense of whether it is good for companies to write climate repor=
ts, and then use that general sense to inform some quick decisions about hu=
ndreds of individual companies.Broadly speaking the trend of the last decad=
e or so in proxy voting is that institutional asset managers used to have a=
 heuristic of =E2=80=9Calways vote with management=E2=80=9D and now they ha=
ve a heuristic of =E2=80=9Cvote for climate-change reports=E2=80=9D? I mean=
, I oversimplify wildly. But as institutional investors talk more and more =
about their commitment to ESG, it becomes more embarrassing for them to vot=
e against ESG proposals. Someone will go collate all their votes and say =
=E2=80=9Cthis firm voted against climate-change proposals in 87% of compani=
es=E2=80=9D or whatever, and that will be embarrassing. And if the giant in=
stitutional manager says =E2=80=9Cwell but we read all of those proposals c=
losely and considered our deep working knowledge of those companies and dec=
ided that a new report was unnecessary in 87% of the cases and necessary in=
 13%,=E2=80=9D one, that will not really satisfy anybody, and two, it proba=
bly won=E2=80=99t be all that true. You were voting on some rough heuristic=
 and now you had better shift your heuristic.Yesterday the SEC proposed a n=
ew rule to make that collating easier:The Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n today proposed amendments to Form N-PX to enhance the information mutual =
funds, exchange-traded funds, and certain other funds report about their pr=
oxy votes. The proposed rulemaking would require funds to tie the descripti=
on of each voting matter to the issuer=E2=80=99s form of proxy and to categ=
orize each matter by type to help investors identify votes of interest and =
compare voting records. The proposal also would prescribe how funds organiz=
e their reports and require them to use a structured data language to make =
the filings easier to analyze. Funds would also be required to disclose how=
 their securities lending activity impacted their voting. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=
=9CThis proposal will make it easier and more efficient for investors to ge=
t crucial information about proxy votes from funds,=E2=80=9D said SEC Chair=
 Gary Gensler. =E2=80=9CI am pleased to support the staff=E2=80=99s recomme=
ndations and look forward to putting them out to public comment.=E2=80=9DSi=
nce 2003, funds have been required to file Form N-PX reports disclosing how=
 they voted on proxy proposals relating to investments they hold, but inves=
tors may face difficulties analyzing these reports. For example, funds may =
report their votes in an inconsistent manner or in a format that is not mac=
hine readable. This can make it more difficult for investors to analyze the=
 reported data. The proposal would make funds=E2=80=99 proxy voting records=
 more usable and easier to analyze, improving investors=E2=80=99 ability to=
 monitor how their funds vote and compare different funds=E2=80=99 voting r=
ecords.Here is the text of the proposed rule, which asks funds to break dow=
n their voting into categories (=E2=80=9Cboard of directors,=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9Caudit-related,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cshareholder rights and defenses,=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccapital structure,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cenvironment or climate=
,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cdiversity, equity and inclusion,=E2=80=9D etc.) and sub=
categories (the subcategories of =E2=80=9Cenvironment or climate=E2=80=9D a=
re =E2=80=9Cgreenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, transition planning or reportin=
g, biodiversity or ecosystem risk, chemical footprint, renewable energy or =
energy efficiency, water issues, waste or pollution, deforestation or land =
use, say-on-climate, environmental justice, or other environment or climate=
 matters=E2=80=9D). The categories and subcategories are listed on pages 36=
 to 39; I count 17 categories and 88 subcategories. The SEC also says that=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe expect that the instructions we are proposing that requir=
e reports on Form N-PX to be structured and machine-readable would allow to=
ols to be developed so that investors can sort and filter the data to view =
votes by the relevant manager.=E2=80=9DThis way, if you want to know how of=
ten BlackRock Inc. votes in favor of shareholder proposals involving =E2=80=
=9Cwater issues,=E2=80=9D you can go use one of those tools and see that Bl=
ackRock voted in favor of =E2=80=9Cwater issues=E2=80=9D proposals in 46% o=
f cases or whatever it is. (To be clear I made that number up; the tools do=
 not exist yet.) And you might say, =E2=80=9CBlackRock, do you not care abo=
ut water?=E2=80=9D And BlackRock will be abashed. You never read any of tho=
se water-issues proposals, and it=E2=80=99s possible that neither did Black=
Rock, but that=E2=80=99s not the point. The point is that there is some sco=
ring system for how many times a fund manager voted for =E2=80=9Cwater issu=
es,=E2=80=9D and some incentive to maximize your score.SEC Commissioner Hes=
ter Peirce dissented from the proposed rules on the grounds that if you tel=
l people too much about how funds vote they will be hijacked by activists:W=
hile fund shareholders may not be interested in this information, activists=
 of every stripe can use the fact that funds have to publish their votes to=
 increase their leverage through intimidation and negative publicity. =C2=
=A0Thus these stakeholders shape how proxy votes are cast.=C2=A0A fund shar=
eholder looking to earn a return so she can retire may not see much value i=
n having the fund manager devote a lot of resources to voting and painstaki=
ngly categorizing the votes for publication. =C2=A0The fund manager, knowin=
g that each vote will be made public, may feel pressured to expend more tim=
e considering the vote and figuring out how to catalog it than she would if=
 the vote were not required to be made public and she were just focused on =
doing what was best for the fund. =C2=A0Eh. I don=E2=80=99t think she=E2=80=
=99s wrong exactly, except that it seems pretty clear that fund shareholder=
s=C2=A0do=C2=A0care about ESG stuff? This is not about activists yelling at=
 fund managers and the managers caving because they are afraid of activists=
. This is about fund managers voting in a way that is reasonably designed t=
o make their customers happy, and having more pressure to do that because t=
he customers can check. Often what makes customers of an asset manager happ=
y is the stocks going up. But that=E2=80=99s clearly not the only thing. Bi=
g asset=C2=A0managers talk a lot about ESG because it sells; the customers =
want ESG.You could just about=C2=A0imagine the person at a big index-fund f=
irm saying =E2=80=9Cwell voting no on this proposal is better for the value=
 of the company, but voting yes on it will make our customers feel better a=
bout our ESG commitments and lead us to amass more assets.=E2=80=9D Which w=
ay do you vote then? I think the cynical commercial answer is =E2=80=9Cvote=
 for ESG,=E2=80=9D but I also think that might be the correct fiduciary ans=
wer? Your obligations, as a fund manager, are to your investors, not to the=
 companies you own.I am kind of fond of this rule? It seems somehow postmod=
ern; it=C2=A0seems to acknowledge a shift in corporate governance. In the o=
lden days, what mattered was the corporation; particular things happened at=
 the corporation, and the shareholders cared very much about that corporati=
on and had particular views on what it should do. In modern markets, the pa=
radigmatic shareholder is broadly diversified, and there is less reason to =
care about what any particular company does. What you want is for the huge =
diversified shareholders who have influence over=C2=A0every=C2=A0company to=
 use that influence in a broadly desirable way. Companies are just data poi=
nts; what you care about is aggregates. We  talked the other day about a sh=
areholder proposal at Fox Corp. that explicitly argued that the proposal mi=
ght be bad for Fox=E2=80=99s bottom line,=C2=A0but will good for all the ot=
her companies that Fox shareholders also own.=C2=A0That is the way of the=
=C2=A0future.Oh by the way the rules also require funds to disclose more cl=
early=C2=A0how many=C2=A0shares they voted, and how many shares they didn=
=E2=80=99t vote because they were out on loan. We have  talked before about=
 my somewhat fanciful theory that the corporate-governance importance of in=
dex funds is overstated because really they lend out lots of shares to shor=
t sellers, don=E2=80=99t recall them for votes, and end up voting fewer sha=
res than they own. I don=E2=80=99t want to overstate it =E2=80=94=C2=A0they=
 don=E2=80=99t usually lend out that many shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I guess=
 we=E2=80=99ll know more about it soon.
