<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Proxy voting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose somewhere out there there ar=
e people who are deeply engaged shareholders of one company. Each year thes=
e people get the company=E2=80=99s proxy statement and read it cover to cov=
er with great interest. Toward the back there are some shareholder proposal=
s, in which shareholders get to suggest changes to how the company is run. =
These proposals typically have an environmental, social or governance (ESG)=
 flavor: A proposal might be =E2=80=9Cthe company should do a report about =
how climate change will affect its operations,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe com=
pany should do a report about the diversity of its managerial ranks,=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe company should separate the jobs of chairman of the boa=
rd and chief executive officer.=E2=80=9D These proposals are nonbinding and=
, under <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.2=
65551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xNGEtOA/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9cb29abf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">Securities and Exchange Commission rules</a>, cannot=
=C2=A0involve =E2=80=9Ca matter relating to the company=E2=80=99s ordinary =
business operations,=E2=80=9D so in practice they often involve asking for =
reports rather than, like, =E2=80=9Cresolved, the company will stop using f=
ossil fuels.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The proposal will com=
e with a little=C2=A0statement from the proponent, the (usually small, acti=
vist) shareholder who suggested it, and also a little=C2=A0statement from t=
he company=E2=80=99s board of directors, almost invariably recommending tha=
t shareholders vote against the proposal. Our deeply engaged single-stock s=
hareholder will read both statements carefully and think about the argument=
s that the proponent and the board make.=C2=A0She will weigh them in the co=
ntext of her knowledge of the company. =E2=80=9CHmm,=E2=80=9D she will say,=
 =E2=80=9CI see what this person is saying about how separating the chairma=
n and CEO roles is best practice, but old Jim has done a great job as CEO a=
nd I=E2=80=99d hate to risk upsetting him by taking away the chairman job.=
=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CI would like to know about how climate change will a=
ffect the company, but I think the board=E2=80=99s track record on that is =
pretty good so I guess I will defer to them.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0and the board=E2=80=99s track record on that is pretty bad so I=E2=80=
=99ll vote to demand more from them.=E2=80=9D Whatever.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t believe there are too many of these pe=
ople but they probably exist. More than individual investors, some number o=
f active stock-picking money managers probably own a relatively small numbe=
r of stocks, track them carefully and vote regularly on their proxy proposa=
ls. These money managers=C2=A0probably do not read the proxies as closely a=
s our hypothetical engaged retail shareholder does. They do this a lot.=C2=
=A0They have heuristics. Maybe they vote against most of these proposals, a=
ssuming that they=E2=80=99re nonbinding and a waste of time. Maybe their he=
uristic is =E2=80=9Cwe vote with management in the companies that we like, =
but we vote against management on everything in companies where we dislike =
the board and are agitating for change.=E2=80=9D Maybe they have issue-spec=
ific heuristics, =E2=80=9Cwe vote for climate-change reports but against di=
versity reports=E2=80=9D or whatever. Probably they have some mishmash of a=
ll of these heuristics, and vote different ways for different proposals at =
different companies, but they don=E2=80=99t spend=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>mu=
ch time thinking about it. These are not retail hobbyists; they have a job =
to do (buying stocks that go up), and voting on proxy proposals is not cent=
ral to that job.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s not irrelevan=
t! Pressuring companies to do ESG things can increase their long-term value=
. A company that has a poison pill or a staggered board might be less likel=
y to be acquired, and depending on your view of whether that would be good =
or bad for the value of your stock, you might care very much about voting o=
n proposals to get rid of a pill or to declassify the board. If you think t=
hat climate change will be very bad for the company and that the board isn=
=E2=80=99t paying attention, you will care a lot about getting the board to=
 pay attention, and a nonbinding request for a report on climate change is,=
 you know, one more thing you could do to get the board to pay attention I =
guess. But mostly this stuff is pretty minor. Companies make money based mo=
stly on how they do their ordinary business, which is specifically off-limi=
ts to shareholder proposals. And even on the big-ticket stuff, companies se=
em to be more responsive to other forms of pressure (quiet nudges from big =
shareholders, social and customer pressure, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.265551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjYvZXh4b24taGFzLWEtdG91Z2gtZ3JlZW4tYWN0=
aXZpc3Q/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3be79a97" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> proxy fights</a>) than they are to nonbin=
ding proposals submitted by small shareholders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Then there are professional money managers who own hundreds of stocks,=
 perhaps all of the stocks, index funds and =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.265551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDItMDkvcXVhc2ktaW5kZXhlcnMtZ3Jvd3R=
oLWFuZC1jb25mdXNpb24/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB09a87e69" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">quasi-indexers</a>.=E2=80=9D =
It seems silly for these professionals to read the proxies at all. (I=E2=80=
=99m sure they do =E2=80=94=C2=A0they have governance and stewardship teams=
 to do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it seems silly.) Certainly if they have to v=
ote on 100 shareholder proposals to write climate reports in a proxy season=
, it would be silly for them to read=C2=A0<em>each=C2=A0</em>of the propone=
nts=E2=80=99 arguments and=C2=A0<em>each=C2=A0</em>of the companies=E2=80=
=99 responses. They=E2=80=99ve seen all this before.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">At this level it is all heuristics. =E2=80=9CVote yes on climate =
proposals=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cvote with management unless we have a little=
 red frowny face next to the company in our huge spreadsheet of investments=
=E2=80=9D or whatever it is. If you own every company, you can=E2=80=99t ha=
ve a close personal substantive relationship with all of them; you can=E2=
=80=99t waste an hour thinking about whether=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>partic=
ular board of directors should or should not write a report about climate c=
hange. You have to have a general sense of whether it is good for companies=
 to write climate reports, and then use that general sense to inform some q=
uick decisions about hundreds of individual companies.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Broadly speaking the trend of the last decade or so in proxy vo=
ting is that institutional asset managers used to have a heuristic of =E2=
=80=9Calways vote with management=E2=80=9D and now they have a heuristic of=
 =E2=80=9Cvote for climate-change reports=E2=80=9D? I mean, I oversimplify =
wildly. But as institutional investors talk more and more about their commi=
tment to ESG, it becomes more embarrassing for them to vote against ESG pro=
posals. Someone will go collate all their votes and say =E2=80=9Cthis firm =
voted against climate-change proposals in 87% of companies=E2=80=9D or what=
ever, and that will be embarrassing. And if the giant institutional manager=
 says =E2=80=9Cwell but we read all of those proposals closely and consider=
ed our deep working knowledge of those companies and decided that a new rep=
ort was unnecessary in 87% of the cases and necessary in 13%,=E2=80=9D one,=
 that will not really satisfy anybody, and two, it probably won=E2=80=99t b=
e all that true. You were voting on some rough heuristic and now you had be=
tter shift your heuristic.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday the SE=
C proposed a new rule to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/25195151.265551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2Uv=
MjAyMS0yMDI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd10844df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">make that collating easier</a>:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n today proposed amendments to Form N-PX to enhance the information mutual =
funds, exchange-traded funds, and certain other funds report about their pr=
oxy votes. The proposed rulemaking would require funds to tie the descripti=
on of each voting matter to the issuer=E2=80=99s form of proxy and to categ=
orize each matter by type to help investors identify votes of interest and =
compare voting records. The proposal also would prescribe how funds organiz=
e their reports and require them to use a structured data language to make =
the filings easier to analyze. Funds would also be required to disclose how=
 their securities lending activity impacted their voting. =E2=80=A6</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis proposal will make it easier and mor=
e efficient for investors to get crucial information about proxy votes from=
 funds,=E2=80=9D said SEC Chair Gary Gensler. =E2=80=9CI am pleased to supp=
ort the staff=E2=80=99s recommendations and look forward to putting them ou=
t to public comment.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since 2003, f=
unds have been required to file Form N-PX reports disclosing how they voted=
 on proxy proposals relating to investments they hold, but investors may fa=
ce difficulties analyzing these reports. For example, funds may report thei=
r votes in an inconsistent manner or in a format that is not machine readab=
le. This can make it more difficult for investors to analyze the reported d=
ata. The proposal would make funds=E2=80=99 proxy voting records more usabl=
e and easier to analyze, improving investors=E2=80=99 ability to monitor ho=
w their funds vote and compare different funds=E2=80=99 voting records.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.265551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZC8yMDIxLzM0LTkzMTY5LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93693e=
d3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the te=
xt of the proposed rule</a>, which asks funds to break down their voting in=
to categories (=E2=80=9Cboard of directors,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Caudit-related=
,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cshareholder rights and defenses,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccapi=
tal structure,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cenvironment or climate,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
diversity, equity and inclusion,=E2=80=9D etc.) and subcategories (the subc=
ategories of =E2=80=9Cenvironment or climate=E2=80=9D are =E2=80=9Cgreenhou=
se gas (GHG) emissions, transition planning or reporting, biodiversity or e=
cosystem risk, chemical footprint, renewable energy or energy efficiency, w=
ater issues, waste or pollution, deforestation or land use, say-on-climate,=
 environmental justice, or other environment or climate matters=E2=80=9D). =
The categories and subcategories are listed on pages 36 to 39; I count 17 c=
ategories and 88 subcategories. The SEC also says that=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe exp=
ect that the instructions we are proposing that require reports on Form N-P=
X to be structured and machine-readable would allow tools to be developed s=
o that investors can sort and filter the data to view votes by the relevant=
 manager.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This way, if you want to=
 know how often BlackRock Inc. votes in favor of shareholder proposals invo=
lving =E2=80=9Cwater issues,=E2=80=9D you can go use one of those tools and=
 see that BlackRock voted in favor of =E2=80=9Cwater issues=E2=80=9D propos=
als in 46% of cases or whatever it is. (To be clear I made that number up; =
the tools do not exist yet.) And you might say, =E2=80=9CBlackRock, do you =
not care about water?=E2=80=9D And BlackRock will be abashed. You never rea=
d any of those water-issues proposals, and it=E2=80=99s possible that neith=
er did BlackRock, but that=E2=80=99s not the point. The point is that there=
 is some scoring system for how many times a fund manager voted for =E2=80=
=9Cwater issues,=E2=80=9D and some incentive to maximize your score.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SEC Commissioner Hester Peirce <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.265551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Vj=
