were just focused on doing what was best for the fund. =C2=A0</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eh. I don=E2=80=99t think she=E2=80=99s wro=
ng exactly, except that it seems pretty clear that fund shareholders=C2=A0<=
em>do=C2=A0</em>care about ESG stuff? This is not about activists yelling a=
t fund managers and the managers caving because they are afraid of activist=
s. This is about fund managers voting in a way that is reasonably designed =
to make their customers happy, and having more pressure to do that because =
the customers can check. Often what makes customers of an asset manager hap=
py is the stocks going up. But that=E2=80=99s clearly not the only thing. B=
ig asset=C2=A0managers talk a lot about ESG because it sells; the customers=
 want ESG.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could just about=C2=A0imagin=
e the person at a big index-fund firm saying =E2=80=9Cwell voting no on thi=
s proposal is better for the value of the company, but voting yes on it wil=
l make our customers feel better about our ESG commitments and lead us to a=
mass more assets.=E2=80=9D Which way do you vote then? I think the cynical =
commercial answer is =E2=80=9Cvote for ESG,=E2=80=9D but I also think that =
might be the correct fiduciary answer? Your obligations, as a fund manager,=
 are to your investors, not to the companies you own.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">I am kind of fond of this rule? It seems somehow postmodern; it=
=C2=A0seems to acknowledge a shift in corporate governance. In the olden da=
ys, what mattered was the corporation; particular things happened at the co=
rporation, and the shareholders cared very much about that corporation and =
had particular views on what it should do. In modern markets, the paradigma=
tic shareholder is broadly diversified, and there is less reason to care ab=
out what any particular company does. What you want is for the huge diversi=
fied shareholders who have influence over=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0</em>company =
to use that influence in a broadly desirable way. Companies are just data p=
oints; what you care about is aggregates. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.265551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMjcvaW1wb3N0b3JzLW9uLXRoZS1kdWUtZGlsaWd=
