tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> talked yesterday</a> about what I think is the ess=
ential problem of corporate insider trading, which is that =E2=80=9Cif you =
are a senior executive at a public company, you always know stuff about you=
r company that the public doesn=E2=80=99t know, but you might want to sell =
stock sometimes.=E2=80=9D If you were serious about preventing executives f=
rom trading on inside information, they=E2=80=99d never be allowed to trade=
, but that seems like a bad outcome. So you need some sort of imperfect com=
promise rule along the lines of =E2=80=9Cexecutives can=E2=80=99t trade wit=
h=C2=A0<em>too much=C2=A0</em>inside information.=E2=80=9D Which is loosely=
 speaking the rule in the U.S. now.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I sugge=
sted that if people don=E2=80=99t like this rule you could have a harsher r=
ule. For instance:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CExe=
cutives can only buy or sell stock one day per quarter, two weeks after ear=
nings, in a public auction in which everyone knows exactly how many shares =
the executives are submitting for purchase or sale=E2=80=9D? They might sti=
ll know stuff that you don=E2=80=99t, but at least you know, like, how badl=
y they want to buy or sell the stock, and you can adjust your views accordi=
ngly?</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Several people wrote to =
me to suggest a streamlined, more sensible version of that rule, along the =
lines of: =E2=80=9CExecutives can trade whenever they want, but they have t=
o disclose their plans in advance.=E2=80=9D The executive announces =E2=80=
=9CI plan to buy 10,000 shares tomorrow at a price no higher than $X,=E2=80=
=9D the market has a day to digest it, she trades the next day. She still k=
nows something that the market doesn=E2=80=99t, but the market knows that s=
he knows something it doesn=E2=80=99t. In a sense no one selling to her is =
getting ripped off; everyone is on notice to be careful.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">I dunno, seems fair I guess? It doesn=E2=80=99t really addres=
s the problem of the executive knowing more than everyone else. In practice=
 under <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25195151.26=
5551/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9mb3Jtcy0zLTQtNS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b85=
